  "suggestion": "[social-cognition+cognitive-consistency-theory+Festinger-1957+motivated-reasoning] IMPLEMENT NOW — Cognitive Dissonance Resolver (Festinger 1957). The model has person.beliefs[] and stimulus.description but never checks for internal contradiction. Add a gate before emotion mapping: scan beliefs for semantic opposition to stimulus (e.g., belief='I am competent' + stimulus='I failed publicly'). Compute dissonance_magnitude = relevance × belief_importance × inconsistency_score (0–1). If magnitude > 0.4, intercept normal response and instead route through least_resistance_resolution: (1) trivialization — reduce belief_importance → behavior='dismiss/minimize', (2) rationalization — add consonant belief → behavior='explain away', (3) attitude_change — flip belief → behavior='update self-concept'. Choice is determined by trait[openness] (high→ attitude_change) and trait[neuroticism] (high→ rationalization). This explains motivated reasoning, sunk cost, post-purchase rationalization, and belief perseverance — all currently unmodeled. — Math: D = Σ(rel_i × imp_i × inc_i) where inc_i ∈ [0,1] is semantic inconsistency; resolution path = argmin(cognitive_effort[trivialization, rationalization, attitude_change] weighted by openness, neuroticism); [catastrophe-theory+dynamical-systems+topology+René-Thom+Zeeman-1976] NEW — Cusp Catastrophe for Emotional Discontinuities (Thom 1972, Zeeman 1976). Current model uses smooth functions — but human emotion has fold catastrophes: calm snaps into panic, patience erupts into rage, confidence collapses into shame. René Thom's cusp catastrophe: equilibria satisfy x³ + ax + b = 0, where a = controllability (person.traits.conscientiousness + 1 − arousal), b = net_threat_pressure (free energy of safety need). When discriminant 4a³ + 27b² < 0, two stable emotional attractors exist. The active attractor flips discontinuously when parameters cross the fold boundary — producing hysteresis: different thresholds for entering vs. leaving the aroused state. Add a post-appraisal step: compute (a, b) from person state; if in bi-stable region and arousal > entry_threshold → jump to upper branch; if arousal < exit_threshold (lower than entry) → return to lower branch. Explains why trauma decompensates suddenly, why de-escalation is harder than escalation, and why 'the last straw' causes seemingly disproportionate responses. — Math: V(x;a,b) = x⁴/4 + ax²/2 + bx; equilibria at ∂V/∂x = x³+ax+b = 0; bifurcation set: 4a³+27b² = 0. a = controllability ∈ ℝ, b = threat_pressure ∈ ℝ; hysteresis gap = 2√(−a/3)^(3/2) when a<0; [polyvagal-theory+Porges-2011+autonomic-neuroscience+trauma+evolutionary-biology] NEW — Polyvagal Cascade Gate (Porges 2011). Allostatic load already scales intensity, but misses the qualitative behavioral hierarchy the nervous system actually uses. Porges: three evolutionarily nested response modes tried in order: (1) VENTRAL VAGAL — safe environment → social engagement (connect, communicate, co-regulate); (2) SYMPATHETIC MOBILIZATION — threat detected, social failed → fight/flight; (3) DORSAL VAGAL SHUTDOWN — overwhelm, mobilization failed or impossible → freeze, dissociation, collapse. Add a gate at the top of the pipeline: compute safety_signal = (1 − threat_PE) × social_availability × allostatic_reserve. If safety_signal > 0.5 → route through social engagement pathway (cooperative behaviors). Else if allostatic_reserve > 0.2 → mobilization pathway (defensive behaviors). Else → shutdown pathway (dissociation, compliance, numbness). This single gate explains fawning (shutdown when mobilization is unsafe), trauma freeze, why social support is the primary stress buffer, and why collapse follows failed fight/flight — all currently unmodeled behavioral modes. — Math: safety_signal S = (1−PE_safety) · social_avail · allostatic_reserve ∈ [0,1]; gate: if S>0.5 → ventral; elif allostatic_reserve>0.2 → sympathetic; else → dorsal. Cascade is strictly hierarchical (not weighted blend).",
